It is often said that Judicial Review is concerned not with the decision but the decision making process. (See eg Chief Constable of North Wales Police v Evans
[1982] 1 WLR 1155
). This proposition, at full face value, may well convey the impression that the jurisdiction of the courts in Judicial Review proceedings is confined to cases where the aggrieved party has not received fair treatment by the authority to which he has been subjected. Put differently, in the words of Lord Diplock in Council of Civil Service Unions & Ors v Minister for the Civil Service [1985] AC 374, where the impugned decision is flawed on the ground of procedural impropriety .

Nevertheless, it is worth noting that a number of Lord Denning's decisions have taken English administrative law further than has generally been accepted and perhaps point the way ahead. Take for example, his willingness to review prerogative power (see Gouriet v UPOW
[1977] 2 WLR 310
; Laker Airways v Department of Trade
[1977] QB 643
), his application of the Continental concept of equality of treatment (see HTV v Price Commission
[1976] ICR 170
), his recognition of the duty to give reasons where a person's livelihood, property and also 'legitimate expectations' are at stake (see Breen v Amalgamated Engineering Union
[1971] 2 QB 175
), the substantive evidence test (see Coleen Properties Ltd v Minister of Housing and Local Government
[1971] 1 WLR 433
) and the requirement not only of procedural fairness but also of substantive fairness (see Chief Constable of North Wales Police v Evans
).

Before I embark upon a response, I should like to point out that it is not without precedent for a dissenter to get answered back by an addition to a joint majority judgment, the addition being drafted by a member of the court who constituted the majority, and the need for which arose because the majority had not had the advantage of reading the dissenting judgment until after the joint majority judgment was written. (See Bradley Egg Farm Ltd v Clifford & Ors
(Court of Appeal (Scott and Goddard LJJ and Bennett J, dissenting) [1943] 2 All ER 378 at p 386
).

In other words, even without O 92 r 4, the inherent powers of High Court would still be there. In the United Kingdom, for instance, there is no provision in the Supreme Court Rules, equivalent to our O 92 r 4, yet the inherent powers occupy a position of great importance in the High Court there as the article by Sir Jack Jacob amply demonstrates. And, the Court of Appeal there also exercises an inherent jurisdiction (see Aviagents v Balstravest Investment Ltd
[1966] 1 WLR 150
) notwithstanding the absence of any provision in any written law or rule of court providing for inherent powers.
